node.text: My guest on Monday’s episode of @jhillunbothered is @yarashahidi. I asked Yara why today’s generation seems more willing to protect their peace than previous ones. We also discuss her entering her last year at Harvard, this current season of Grown-ish, and what it was like growing up around Prince. To listen to this podcast and others, CLICK THE LINK IN MY BIO.

node.title: Yara Shahidi on the mentality of today’s generation

node.text:
Last year, I had a big ol’ party planned for my husband @woodbigsity but COVID-19 had other plans. This year, I decided to run it back and although it wasn’t the party I initially had in mind because of the pandemic, it turned out EVEN BETTER. The theme was Coming to America and we had everything from live animals to dancers to rose petal girls. Like, Ferris Bueller said: “You can never go too far.” Happy birthday baby! #40thReloaded #Wood2America

node.text:
Lately we’ve inundated with clips of the worst people acting completely unhinged at school board, county and community meetings. Honestly, it has inspired me to make sure I attend some meeting in my own community. We have to stop letting stupid people and bad faith actors hijack and dictate the conversation. We also need to stop assuming that these people acting this way publicly aren’t a threat. Democracies crumble because of apathy, and when good people are silent and complacent. Anyway, we need more people like this dude at public meetings. Normalize this shit.

*LATE ADD*
Just found out this is @justinkanew. Thank you Justin for saying what needed to be said.

node.text:
My mother was among those who was extremely hesitant about getting the vaccine. She is NOT an anti-vaxxed, but someone whose is immunocompromised and therefore understandably concerned about how her body might react to the vaccines. After months of research — my mother has a background in medical laboratory medicine — my mother decided to get the Johnson & Johnson vaccine because per her doctors advice, that was the best one that suited her given her medical history and issues. 

I understand vaccine hesitancy. It’s normal and warranted. But PLEASE talk these concerns out with a medical professional. Facebook memes, conspiracy theories, word of mouth and general misinformation have unfortunately worked to a large degree. 

Anyway, a couple months ago I did an entire podcast breaking down vaccine fears in the Black community with my mom. I interviewed the black virologist who was on the FDA board that authorized the vaccines for emergency use, and other black experts who understand the history of medical racism in this country. LINK IS IN MY BIO. I encourage you to listen to the pod and get the information FROM ACTUAL EXPERTS.

Also … i can’t wait for my Mom to visit me!

node.text:
COMING MONDAY: A new episode of @jhillunbothered featuring @mspattilabelle. We discuss her incrediblecareer, her friendship with Aretha Franklin, and why she rejects being labeled a diva. But since Patti is a well-regarded chef, I had her settle a debate I have all the time with my husband @woodbigsity about whether you should cook food after its expiration date. Patti settles the debate once and for all.

ALSO: Listen and subscribe to the podcast. Previous episodes from this season include: @therealmaryjblige @missjillscott @michaelbjordan @tamikadmallory … LINK TO LISTEN IS IN MY BIO.

node.title: Patti Labelle settles an important argument

While I didn’t agree with everything that was said, the George Floyd Justice in Policing Act must move forward to lay the groundwork for meaningful disruption. That means ending qualified immunity. We need creative, progressive drastic solutions. Anyway, to see this FULL conversation, LINK IS IN MY BIO.

node.text:
Lately we’ve inundated with clips of the worst people acting completely unhinged at school board, county and community meetings. Honestly, it has inspired me to make sure I attend some meeting in my own community. We have to stop letting stupid people and bad faith actors hijack and dictate the conversation. We also need to stop assuming that these people acting this way publicly aren’t a threat. Democracies crumble because of apathy, and when good people are silent and complacent. Anyway, we need more people like this dude at public meetings. Normalize this shit.

*LATE ADD*
Just found out this is @justinkanew. Thank you Justin for saying what needed to be said.

node.text:
My mother was among those who was extremely hesitant about getting the vaccine. She is NOT an anti-vaxxed, but someone whose is immunocompromised and therefore understandably concerned about how her body might react to the vaccines. After months of research — my mother has a background in medical laboratory medicine — my mother decided to get the Johnson & Johnson vaccine because per her doctors advice, that was the best one that suited her given her medical history and issues. 

I understand vaccine hesitancy. It’s normal and warranted. But PLEASE talk these concerns out with a medical professional. Facebook memes, conspiracy theories, word of mouth and general misinformation have unfortunately worked to a large degree. 

Anyway, a couple months ago I did an entire podcast breaking down vaccine fears in the Black community with my mom. I interviewed the black virologist who was on the FDA board that authorized the vaccines for emergency use, and other black experts who understand the history of medical racism in this country. LINK IS IN MY BIO. I encourage you to listen to the pod and get the information FROM ACTUAL EXPERTS.

Also … i can’t wait for my Mom to visit me!
